JavaScript me `async/await` asynchronous programming ko asaan banata hai. Jab aap kisi function ko `async` declare karte hain, ye promise return karta hai. `await` ka use aap kisi promise ko resolve karne ke liye karte hain. Yeh aapko synchronous tarike se likhne ki ijazat deta hai.

Example ke liye:

```javascript
function fetchData() {
  return new Promise((resolve) => {
    setTimeout(() => {
      resolve('Data fetched!');
    }, 2000);
  });
}

async function getData() {
  const data = await fetchData();
  console.log(data);
}

getData(); // Yeh 2 seconds baad 'Data fetched!' print karega.
```

Is example me, `fetchData` function ek promise return karta hai aur usay `await` ke sath use karne se result milta hai bina kisi callback ya `.then()` ke.

React ka `useEffect` hook aapko component ke lifecycle events ko manage karne ki suvidha deta hai. Ye function component ke andar side effects handle karne ke liye use hota hai, jaise data fetching, subscriptions, ya manually DOM updates. 

Iska syntax kuch is tarah hai: 

```javascript
import React, { useEffect } from 'react';

function MyComponent() {
    useEffect(() => {
        // Yeh code run hoga jab component mount hoga
        console.log('Component mounted');

        return () => {
            // Yeh code run hoga jab component unmount hoga
            console.log('Component unmounted');
        };
    }, []); // Dependency array, agar empty hai to sirf mount aur unmount pe chalega

    return <div>Hello, World!</div>;
}
```

Is example mein `useEffect` hook tab chalega jab `MyComponent` pehli dafa render hoga. Agar aap dependency array mein koi variable dalte hain, to `useEffect` tab chalega jab wo variable change hota hai.

