JavaScript mein variables declare karne ke liye teen keywords hain: `var`, `let`, aur `const`. Inka farq ye hai:

1. **var**: Ye purana tareeqa hai, aur iska scope function ke andar hota hai. Iska use karne se variable ko function ke andar ya bahar declare kiya ja sakta hai.
   ```javascript
   function test() {
       var x = 10;
       if (true) {
           var x = 20; // same variable
           console.log(x); // 20
       }
       console.log(x); // 20
   }
   test();
   ```

2. **let**: Ye block scope ke liye use hota hai. Isse aap variable ko sirf us block ke andar access kar sakte hain jahan ye define hui hai.
   ```javascript
   function test() {
       let y = 10;
       if (true) {
           let y = 20; // different variable
           console.log(y); // 20
       }
       console.log(y); // 10
   }
   test();
   ```

3. **const**: Ye bhi block scope ke liye hai, lekin iski value ko aap change nahi kar sakte. Ye read-only hota hai.
   ```javascript
   const z = 10;
   console.log(z); // 10
   // z = 20; // Error: Assignment to constant variable.
   ```

Is tarah se aap variables ka istemal karte hain JavaScript mein.

