JWT (JSON Web Token) ek standard hai jo user ko authenticate karne ke liye use hota hai. Jab user login karta hai, toh server ek JWT token generate karta hai jo user ki identity aur permissions ko represent karta hai. Is token ko client side par store kiya jata hai, aur har request ke sath isay server ko bhejna hota hai. Yeh ek secure tareeqa hai authentication ka. Code mein aise use hota hai:

```javascript
// Express.js example
const jwt = require('jsonwebtoken');

// User login function
function login(req, res) {
    const user = { id: 1, username: 'example' }; // Example user
    const token = jwt.sign(user, 'secretKey'); // JWT token generate karna
    res.json({ token }); // Token ko response mein bhejna
}

// Middleware to verify token
function authenticateToken(req, res, next) {
    const token = req.headers['authorization'];
    if (!token) return res.sendStatus(401);
    jwt.verify(token, 'secretKey', (err, user) => {
        if (err) return res.sendStatus(403);
        req.user = user;
        next();
    });
}
```
Is tarah se aap JWT ko authentication ke liye implement kar sakte hain.

Redux aur Context API dono state management ke liye use hote hain, lekin inka istemal karne ka tareeqa aur features thore alag hain. Redux ek centralized store provide karta hai jahan aapki application ki state store hoti hai. Ye complex applications ke liye behtar hota hai kyunki isme middleware aur dev tools hain jo debugging mein madadgar hote hain. Yahan ek chhota sa example hai:

