Repository pattern aik software design pattern hai jo data access ko abstract karta hai. Ye application layer aur data access layer ke darmiyan aik interface provide karta hai, taake data source ko change karna asaan ho. Is pattern ka istemal aksar applications mein hota hai jahan data ko database, API, ya kisi aur source se fetch karna hota hai. Acha example hai:

```csharp
public interface IUserRepository {
    User GetUserById(int id);
    IEnumerable<User> GetAllUsers();
}

public class UserRepository : IUserRepository {
    private readonly DbContext _context;

    public UserRepository(DbContext context) {
        _context = context;
    }

    public User GetUserById(int id) {
        return _context.Users.Find(id);
    }

    public IEnumerable<User> GetAllUsers() {
        return _context.Users.ToList();
    }
}
```

Is example mein, `IUserRepository` interface hai jo data access methods define karta hai, aur `UserRepository` class isay implement karti hai taake actual database se data fetch kar sake.

Design patterns programming mein reusable solutions hain jo common problems ke liye use hote hain. Singleton pattern ka matlab hai ek hi instance create karna. Iska istemal aise situations mein hota hai jahan sirf ek object chahiye. Factory pattern ek interface ya class hai jo objects ko create karne ke liye use hota hai. Dekh code ke saath: 

```python
# Singleton Pattern
class Singleton:
    _instance = None

    def __new__(cls):
        if cls._instance is None:
            cls._instance = super(Singleton, cls).__new__(cls)
        return cls._instance

# Factory Pattern
class AnimalFactory:
    @staticmethod
    def create_animal(animal_type):
        if animal_type == "Dog":
            return Dog()
        elif animal_type == "Cat":
            return Cat()
        return None
```

Design patterns programming mein reuse aur maintainability ko enhance karte hain. Singleton pattern ka matlab hai ke aap ek class ka sirf ek hi instance create karte hain. Ye is liye hota hai ke aapko globally accessible object chahiye hota hai. Example:

```python
class Singleton:
    _instance = None

    def __new__(cls):
        if cls._instance is None:
            cls._instance = super(Singleton, cls).__new__(cls)
        return cls._instance
```

Factory pattern aapko object create karne ke liye ek interface provide karta hai, taake aap complex object creation details ko hide kar sakein. Example:

```python
class Animal:
    def speak(self):
        pass

class Dog(Animal):
    def speak(self):
        return 'Woof!'

class Cat(Animal):
    def speak(self):
        return 'Meow!'

class AnimalFactory:
    @staticmethod
    def create_animal(animal_type):
        if animal_type == 'dog':
            return Dog()
        elif animal_type == 'cat':
            return Cat()

factory = AnimalFactory()
animal = factory.create_animal('dog')
print(animal.speak())  # Output: Woof!
```

Is tarah, Singleton aur Factory patterns aapko code ko behter tarike se manage karne mein madad dete hain.

Singleton design pattern aik aisa design pattern hai jismein hum ensure karte hain ke class ka sirf aik instance hi banayega. Yeh use hota hai jab hume kisi resource ko globally access karna ho. Yeh code example dekhein:

```javascript
class Singleton {
    constructor() {
        if (!Singleton.instance) {
            Singleton.instance = this;
        }
        return Singleton.instance;
    }
}

const instance1 = new Singleton();
const instance2 = new Singleton();

console.log(instance1 === instance2); // true
```

Is example mein, jab bhi aap `Singleton` class ka naya object banate hain, yeh hamesha pehla instance hi return karta hai.

React ka useEffect hook functional components mein side effects manage karne ke liye use hota hai. Ye component ke render hone par kuch actions perform karne ki ijazat deta hai, jaise data fetch karna ya subscriptions create karna. Example ke liye:

```javascript
import React, { useEffect } from 'react';

function ExampleComponent() {
  useEffect(() => {
    console.log('Component mounted!');

    return () => {
