Express.js mein routing kaafi asaan hai. Aap `express.Router()` ka use karke alag routes bana sakte hain. Yahan par ek simple example hai: 

```javascript
const express = require('express');
const app = express();

// Home route
app.get('/', (req, res) => {
    res.send('Home Page');
});

// About route
app.get('/about', (req, res) => {
    res.send('About Page');
});

app.listen(3000, () => {
    console.log('Server is running on port 3000');
});
```

Is code mein, hum ne do routes define kiye hain: `'/'` aur `'/about'`. Jab bhi koi in routes par request karta hai, to respective message display hota hai.

Haan, Express.js mein aap parameters use kar sakte hain routes mein. Ye kaafi useful hote hain jab aapko dynamic data pass karna hota hai. Jaise ki is example mein: 

```javascript
const express = require('express');
const app = express();

// User profile route with parameter
app.get('/user/:id', (req, res) => {
    const userId = req.params.id;
    res.send(`User ID is: ${userId}`);
});

app.listen(3000, () => {
    console.log('Server is running on port 3000');
});
```

Is code mein, `:id` ek parameter hai jo aapke route mein dynamically replace hota hai. Jab aap `/user/123` request karte hain, to aapko `User ID is: 123` milta hai.
